<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Computer Scence 39C (Spring 1997), 2 Units</H2>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><TABLE WIDTH="450" BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="2" CELLPADDING=
"0">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="24%"><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/logo.gif" WIDTH="90" HEIGHT="83" ALIGN="BOTTOM"
HSPACE="18" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="76%"><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Communications Infrastructures and Mobile Computing: From
Smoke Signals to the Internet, From the Abacus to the Handheld Computer</H2>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</P>

<P>It has long been the dream of humankind to be able to communicate any
where, any place, and any time. The possession of such an ability, and the
timely information it would provide, would ensure the power of kings, nation
states, and business cartels. So it is not surprising that communications
was among the first examples of state-sponsored research.</P>

<P>In this seminar, we will discuss the history and evolution of communications
systems and computing devices, from the days of Ancient Greece to the present.
We will examine how the inventors of early systems developed features such
as secret codes, error correction, and &quot;traffic control,&quot; which
are common in today's communications infrastructures. We will also describe
the scientists, inventors, and entrepreneurs who made today's trillion dollar
information and communications industry possible. In a similar fashion,
we will examine how the evolution of computers has recently resulted in
pocket-sized devices that communicate over the airwaves, and how the convergence
of mobile computing and communications is finally allowing us to realize
the &quot;information anywhere, any place, anytime&quot; vision.</P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H2>Course Instructors</H2>

<UL>
  <LI><A HREF="http://www.cs.Berkeley.edu/~randy">Professor Randy H. Katz</A>
