<H2>Course Outline</H2>

<H3><HR ALIGN=LEFT>Session #1: Communications Before the Industrial Age</H3>

<H4><A HREF="beginning/beginning.html">In the Beginning ...</A></H4>

<P><TABLE WIDTH="450" BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="2" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="17%"><IMG SRC="gifs/greek.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="57" HEIGHT="96" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="83%">A discussion of the earliest forms of sending messages over great distances:
runners (where does the marathon come from?), horse relays (before the Pony
express!), homing pigeons, smoke signals (Polybius' alphabetic code), torch
signaling, heliographs (flashing mirrors), signal flags (especially in the
Navy). Recurring themes: methods for efficiently coding information, ways
to insure the secrecy of information being transmitted, what it takes to
construct infrastructures that span a region, how to synchronize senders
and receivers, the separation of control messages from data message.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</P>

<H5>Readings</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <UL>
    <LI><A HREF="http://tmpwww.electrum.kth.se/docs/early_net/ch-1-1.html">Experimental
    Hypertext Version of &quot;The Early History of Data Networks,&quot; Chapter
    1: Torches and Beacons</A>
    <LI><A HREF="http://www.sfmuseum.org/hist1/pxpress.html">When the Pony
    Express was in Vogue</A>
  </UL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H4><A HREF="optical/optical.html">Napoleon's Secret Weapon: The Optical
Telegraph</A></H4>

<H5><TABLE WIDTH="450" BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="2" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="20%"><IMG SRC="gifs/napolean.gif" WIDTH="73" HEIGHT="80" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="80%">Encoding of common messages and characters in symbolic form. Cryptography
and secret writing. &quot;Telegraph: writing at a distance.&quot; Information
traveling faster than the quickest form of transportation. Development of
the optical telegraph (aka &quot;wig wag&quot;) in the late 18th Century.
Deployment of the first optical telegraph SYSTEM in France and its use in
the French Revolution and the Napoleanic wars. 5000 km and 556 stations
by mid-1800s. First recorded use of error control (resend a lost character),
flow control (send faster, send slower), and message priority. Alternative
systems, such as the octal encoded shutter systems of England and Sweden.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
Readings</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <UL>
    <LI><A HREF="http://tmpwww.electrum.kth.se/docs/early_net/ch-1-2.html">Experimental
    Hypertext Version of &quot;The Early History of Data Networks&quot;, Chapter
    2: Claude Chappe</A>
    <LI><A HREF="http://www.telemuseum.se/historia/optel/optteleng.html">The
    Optical Telegraph System in Sweden 1794 - 1881</A>
  </UL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><TABLE WIDTH="450" BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="2" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="82%"><P><I>Engineer/Entrepreneur</I>: <BR>
Claude Chappe</P>

<P><I>Experiment</I>: <BR>
Use mirrors and/or flashlights to send and receive messages between Grizzly
Peak and the Berkeley Pier.</TD>
<TD WIDTH="18%"><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="gifs/chappe.gif" WIDTH="58" HEIGHT="75" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<H3>Session #2: Dots and Dashes Span the Globe</H3>

<H4>&quot;What Hath God Wrought&quot;: The Electromechanical Telegraph</H4>

<P>Electromagnetism discoveries (e.g., Cooke and Wheatstone) leading up
to Samuel F. B. Morse's invention of the Morse Code and his system for its
transmission in 1844. First U.S. government funded demonstration: Morse's
system between Baltimore and Washington. Telegraphy and its relationship
to the railroads. The inventor as an entrepreneur and how the telegraph
infrastructure was financed and deployed in US and elsewhere. The development
of submarine telegraph cables and the great adventure to span the Atlantic
in 1850s and 60s, and then the world. Lord Kelvin's contributions to long
distance, submarine telegraph technology. The nationally sponsored telegraphic
cartels. Communications as a driver of imperialism and international politics:
the desire for the &quot;all red&quot; route.</P>

<H5>Readings</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <UL>
    <LI><A HREF="http://www.mediahistory.com/graph.html">The Media History
    Project Connections Page on Telegraphy</A>
    <LI><A HREF="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/76.html">National Inventors
    Hall of Fame: Samuel F. B. Morse</A>
    <LI><A HREF="http://web.mit.edu/invent/www/inventorsI-Q/morse.html">MIT's
    Invention Dimension: Samuel F. B. Morse</A>
    <LI><A HREF="http://www.ieee.org/history_center/general_info/programs_and_projects/exhibits/lines_and_waves/lines_menu.html">Michael
    Faraday and James Clerk Maxwell</A>
  </UL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<H4>&quot;Look Ma, No Wires&quot;: Marconi and the Invention of Radio</H4>

<P>Political context: how to circumvent the existing national monopolies
for telegraphic lines. Technology build up to Marconi's invention: Maxwell's
electromagnetic waves and Hertz's oscillators. Marconi's early experiments
with spark gap transmitters and coherer receivers in 1895. Marconi as the
Bill Gates of his age: inventor, promoter, and businessman. Marconi spans
the Atlantic in 1901 with long wave transmission and the discovery of the
Ionosphere. Marconi's Wireless Monopoly. International treaties to deal
with the issues of spectrum allocation and managment across national boundaries.</P>

<H5>Readings</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <UL>
    <LI><A HREF="http://eagle.uccb.ns.ca/steve/marconi/marconi.html">A Brief
    History of Marconi's Three Trans-Atlantic Radio Stations in Cape Breton</A>
    <LI><A HREF="http://www.mediahistory.com/radio.html">The Media History
    Project Connections Page on Radio</A>
    <LI><A HREF="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/71.html">National Inventors
    Hall of Fame: Guglielmo Marconi</A>
  </UL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><TABLE WIDTH="450" BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="2" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="66%"><P>&nbsp;<I>Inventor/Scientist/Entrepreneur</I>: <BR>
